27:46.624 --> 27:48.960
I met an Indian woman there.

27:49.127 --> 27:51.338
In the Americas.

27:52.672 --> 27:54.382
She had an apple cart.

27:54.549 --> 27:56.593
Sold pound cakes in the morning.

27:56.760 --> 27:58.720
Skin like a brick.

27:58.887 --> 28:03.016
I asked her name
and she said, "Susan."

28:03.183 --> 28:05.101
A woman like her called "Susan"?

28:05.268 --> 28:07.437
I said, "What name
were you born to?"

28:07.604 --> 28:10.732
And she just said,
"I'm Susan now."

28:12.400 --> 28:15.528
In the Americas, anyone can be
anything they insist upon.

28:15.695 --> 28:21.743
New name, new life.
That's a place a body could be happy.

28:21.910 --> 28:24.079
What the fuck is happy?

28:24.245 --> 28:26.206
Fucked if I know.

28:28.375 --> 28:30.752
I think I knew
when I was a little girl.

28:31.795 --> 28:33.713
Sitting on the shingle
waiting for me father's boat

28:33.880 --> 28:35.256
to return from sea.

28:35.423 --> 28:38.259
Now I'd be content
to be content.

28:39.636 --> 28:43.181
A home, a tree.

28:44.599 --> 28:46.810
Someone kind enough to be by me.

28:48.061 --> 28:49.729
Not too kind.

28:49.896 --> 28:52.107
I've been living on my boots

28:52.273 --> 28:54.818
and out of my pockets
long since I can remember.

28:56.277 --> 28:57.904
You could get lucky.

28:58.071 --> 28:59.489
Do alright there.

28:59.656 --> 29:01.366
The fuck would I do
in the Americas?

29:01.533 --> 29:03.284
Deliver gold to their king.

29:04.452 --> 29:06.246
They don't have a king.

29:06.413 --> 29:07.914
Not yet.

29:09.040 --> 29:10.708
Everyone needs a king.

29:47.704 --> 29:50.331
Is it this cold
in here every night?

30:02.886 --> 30:04.637
<i>The condemned never know</i>

30:04.804 --> 30:07.307
<i>when the hangman
has coiled his noose.</i>

30:16.483 --> 30:18.026
I, uh...

30:20.069 --> 30:23.239
I brought this food myself,
from the kitchen.

30:23.406 --> 30:26.451
Fresh bread, fresh fruit.

30:26.618 --> 30:28.286
Meat pie.

30:32.874 --> 30:36.836
Such a shame, to let you go to waste
at the gallows. Hmm.

30:37.003 --> 30:41.216
<i>The Warden of Newgate then
made three factual statements.</i>

30:41.382 --> 30:43.301
<i>That it would be
a good 12 weeks</i>

30:43.468 --> 30:45.094
<i>before her case would be heard,</i>

30:45.261 --> 30:49.057
<i>that she was, to his mind,
a very pretty thing,</i>

30:49.224 --> 30:52.810
<i>and that there was a way
that she might, luck smiling,</i>

30:52.977 --> 30:55.271
<i>escape the gallows yet.</i>

31:05.990 --> 31:07.450
Ah!

31:07.617 --> 31:09.285
Oh!

31:10.411 --> 31:11.871
<i>When her turn came,</i>

31:12.038 --> 31:14.582
<i>Essie shocked no-one
by pleading her belly.</i>

31:14.749 --> 31:17.710
<i>The town matrons
who assessed such claims,</i>

31:17.877 --> 31:20.004
<i>which were usually spurious,</i>

31:20.171 --> 31:22.048
<i>were surprised
when they were forced to agree</i>

31:22.215 --> 31:25.385
<i>Essie was indeed with child.</i>

31:29.639 --> 31:31.182
<i>Her sentence of death</i>

31:31.349 --> 31:34.519
<i>was once more commuted
to transportation,</i>

31:34.686 --> 31:37.105
<i>this time for life.</i>

31:37.272 --> 31:38.856
<i>In her days ever after,</i>

31:39.023 --> 31:41.859
<i>she would have nightmares
of her time in that hold.</i>

32:08.928 --> 32:11.848
<i>The 'Sea-Maiden' landed
at Norfolk in Virginia,</i>

32:12.015 --> 32:14.892
<i>and Essie's indenture was bought
by a tobacco farmer</i>

32:15.059 --> 32:17.186
<i>named John Richardson,</i>

32:17.353 --> 32:19.230
<i>for his wife had died of fever</i>

32:19.397 --> 32:21.566
<i>a week after giving birth
to his daughter,</i>

32:21.733 --> 32:23.943
<i>and he had need of a wet nurse</i>

32:24.110 --> 32:27.488
<i>and a maid of all work
upon his small holding.</i>

32:46.716 --> 32:48.593
<i>And along with her milk,</i>

32:48.760 --> 32:52.930
<i>the children, as they grew,
drank Essie's tales.</i>

32:58.770 --> 33:01.439
♪ But the willow-man

33:01.606 --> 33:05.652
♪ Goes walking

33:05.818 --> 33:11.324
♪ Walking if you stay out. ♪

33:34.138 --> 33:35.765
Quit it, you fucking baby.

33:36.808 --> 33:38.559
We're not all hanger steaks.

33:52.865 --> 33:54.826
Have at it.

33:54.992 --> 33:57.453
Seeing as how my stomach
is sewn shut and not connected

33:57.620 --> 33:59.831
to the organs of digestion,
I think I will pass.

33:59.997 --> 34:01.958
You'll be eating again
soon enough.

34:02.125 --> 34:03.584
If your resurrection guy
can do it.

34:03.751 --> 34:07.422
Can and will, for a favour.
If not for gold.

34:11.926 --> 34:14.178
How much gold do you have?

34:14.345 --> 34:16.806
- How much is in a hoard?
- What the fuck is a hoard?

34:16.973 --> 34:18.683
Why do you have one?

34:20.059 --> 34:21.477
I was a king, once.

34:21.644 --> 34:22.687
OK.

34:22.854 --> 34:26.065
I was. Then they made me a bird.

34:26.232 --> 34:27.859
Then Mother Church came along

34:28.025 --> 34:31.362
and turned us all into saints,
and trolls and faeries.

34:31.529 --> 34:33.489
General Mills did the rest.

34:33.656 --> 34:35.032
So what's the appeal?

34:35.199 --> 34:36.617
What's Wednesday selling

34:36.784 --> 34:38.786
at this god-fest
that you've got to get a ticket?

34:40.830 --> 34:42.331
War.

34:47.211 --> 34:49.088
I went to war once.

34:50.131 --> 34:51.716
Or was meant to.

34:52.842 --> 34:54.594
Long time back.

34:55.762 --> 34:59.015
On the eve of battle,
I looked into the fire...

35:01.100 --> 35:04.312
..and I saw my death,
sure as Sunday.

35:04.479 --> 35:06.397
I saw.

35:22.580 --> 35:26.083
I knew I would die that day
if I stayed.

35:31.339 --> 35:33.216
I put on my boots...

35:34.342 --> 35:38.346
..and dropped my sword,
and I flew.

35:44.560 --> 35:46.145
I owe a battle.

35:49.315 --> 35:50.691
You're following Wednesday

35:50.858 --> 35:52.735
so that you can fight in his war
and die?

35:52.902 --> 35:55.321
And for that,
you run his errands?

35:57.323 --> 35:59.325
I've done worse than that.

36:01.536 --> 36:03.037
Dying worked for me.

36:03.204 --> 36:05.456
Everyone should try it
at least once.

36:05.623 --> 36:07.792
Seems like you've walked the earth
a couple hundred years

36:07.959 --> 36:10.628
in those boots already,
so you're due.

37:25.036 --> 37:26.746
The night of Samhain,

37:26.913 --> 37:29.832
the spirits can spill freely
into our world,

37:29.999 --> 37:33.794
but if you wear a disguise,
like that,

37:33.961 --> 37:36.464
then they'll take you
for one of their own.

37:36.631 --> 37:38.674
- The horsie's coming!
- Yes, your daddy's home.

37:38.841 --> 37:41.802
But we have to pay
special mind of who?

37:41.969 --> 37:43.387
The lep...

37:43.554 --> 37:44.889
..prechaun.

37:45.056 --> 37:46.849
Leprechaun! That's right.

37:47.016 --> 37:50.603
So we just leave a small ration
from our harvest.

37:50.770 --> 37:53.689
'Cause if they so choose,
they can lead you off the path

37:53.856 --> 37:55.650
you've trod
a thousand times before.

37:58.527 --> 38:00.404
<i>She told them
all these things</i>

38:00.571 --> 38:05.076
<i>and they believed
because she believed.</i>

38:19.382 --> 38:22.551
Sorry. I just finished up, sir.

38:25.930 --> 38:28.683
Well, goodnight,
Master Richardson.

38:28.849 --> 38:31.018
Wait.

38:36.691 --> 38:38.567
Master Richardson.

38:41.278 --> 38:44.699
